.SH NAME
dotty-env-use - Fill a template with credential references.


.SH SYNOPSIS
\fBdotty env use [--in-file=] [--out-file=] [flags]\fP


.SH DESCRIPTION
Replace every {{ dotty:/// }} reference (and bare {{ KEY }}
resolved against --namespace) in a template with its value, the way op inject
does. The template is read from --in-file or stdin and written to --out-file
(created with 0600) or stdout. An unknown or malformed reference is an error,
and an --out-file is written atomically so a failed run leaves no partial file.


.SH OPTIONS
\fB-h\fP, \fB--help\fP[=false]
	help for use

.PP
\fB--in-file\fP=""
	template file to read (default: stdin)

.PP
\fB--out-file\fP=""
	file to write, created with 0600 (default: stdout)


.SH OPTIONS INHERITED FROM PARENT COMMANDS
\fB--namespace\fP="default"
	credential namespace to operate on

.PP
\fB--profile\fP=""
	profile to operate on (defaults to the active profile)


.SH EXAMPLE
.EX
  dotty env use --in-file=.env.tmpl --out-file=.env
  echo 'token={{ dotty://ci/GITHUB_TOKEN }}' | dotty env use
.EE


.SH SEE ALSO
\fBdotty-env(1)\fP
